# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nash-equilibrium-computation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] Among hundreds of fixed-point theorems, Brouwer's is particularly well known, due in part to its use across numerous fields of mathematics.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] In its original field, this result is one of the key theorems characterizing the topology of Euclidean spaces, along with the Jordan curve theorem, the hairy ball theorem, the invariance of dimension and the Borsuk–Ulam theorem.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] This gives it a place among the fundamental theorems of topology.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The theorem is also used for proving deep results about differential equations and is covered in most introductory courses on differential geometry.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] It appears in unlikely fields such as game theory.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] In economics, Brouwer's fixed-point theorem and its extension, the Kakutani fixed-point theorem, play a central role in the proof of existence of general equilibrium in market economies as developed in the 1950s by economics Nobel prize winners Kenneth Arrow and Gérard Debreu.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The theorem was first studied in view of work on differential equations by the French mathematicians around Henri Poincaré and Charles Émile Picard.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] Proving results such as the Poincaré–Bendixson theorem requires the use of topological methods.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] This work at the end of the 19th century opened into several successive versions of the theorem.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The case of differentiable mappings of the *n*-dimensional closed ball was first proved in 1910 by Jacques Hadamard and the general case for continuous mappings by Brouwer in 1911.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The theorem has several formulations, depending on the context in which it is used and its degree of generalization.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The theorem holds only for functions that are *endomorphisms* (functions that have the same set as the domain and codomain) and for nonempty sets that are *compact* (thus, in particular, bounded and closed) and *convex* (or homeomorphic to convex).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The following examples show why the pre-conditions are important.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] which is a continuous function from $\mathbb {R}$ to itself.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] As it shifts every point to the right, it cannot have a fixed point.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The space $\mathbb {R}$ is convex and closed, but not bounded.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] which is a continuous function from the open interval $(-1,1)$ to itself.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] Since the point $x=1$ is not part of the interval, there is no point in the domain such that $f(x)=x$ .
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The set $(-1,1)$ is convex and bounded, but not closed.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] On the other hand, the function f does have a fixed point in the *closed* interval $[-1,1]$ , namely $x=1$ .
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The closed interval $[-1,1]$ is compact, the open interval $(-1,1)$ is not.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] Convexity is not strictly necessary for Brouwer's fixed-point theorem.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] Because the properties involved (continuity, being a fixed point) are invariant under homeomorphisms, Brouwer's fixed-point theorem is equivalent to forms in which the domain is required to be a closed unit ball $D^{n}$ .
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] For the same reason it holds for every set that is homeomorphic to a closed ball (and therefore also closed, bounded, connected, without holes, etc.).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The following example shows that Brouwer's fixed-point theorem does not work for domains with holes.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] Consider the function $f(x)=-x$ , which is a continuous function from the unit circle to itself.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] Since $-x\neq x$ holds for any point of the unit circle, f has no fixed point.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The analogous example works for the n -dimensional sphere (or any symmetric domain that does not contain the origin).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The unit circle is closed and bounded, but it has a hole (and so it is not convex).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The function f *does* have a fixed point for the unit disc, since it takes the origin to itself.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] A formal generalization of Brouwer's fixed-point theorem for "hole-free" domains can be derived from the Lefschetz fixed-point theorem.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] In game theory, a **correlated equilibrium** is a solution concept that is more general than the well known Nash equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] It was first discussed by mathematician Robert Aumann in 1974.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] The idea is that each player chooses their action according to their private observation of the value of the same public signal.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] A strategy assigns an action to every possible observation a player can make.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] If no player would want to deviate from their strategy (assuming the others also don't deviate), the distribution from which the signals are drawn is called a correlated equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] An N -player strategic game $\displaystyle (N,\{A_{i}\},\{u_{i}\})$ is characterized by an action set $A_{i}$ and utility function $u_{i}$ for each player i .
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] When player i chooses strategy $a_{i}\in A_{i}$ and the remaining players choose a strategy profile described by the $(N-1)$ -tuple $a_{-i}$ , then player i 's utility is $\displaystyle u_{i}(a_{i},a_{-i})$ .
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] A *strategy modification* for player i is a function $\phi _{i}\colon A_{i}\to A_{i}$ .
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] That is, $\phi _{i}$ tells player i to modify his behavior by playing action $\phi _{i}(a_{i})$ when instructed to play $a_{i}$ .
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] Let $(\Omega ,\pi )$ be a countable probability space.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] For each player i , let $P_{i}$ be his information partition, $q_{i}$ be i 's posterior probability and let $s_{i}\colon \Omega \rightarrow A_{i}$ , assigning the same value to states in the same cell of i 's information partition.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] In other words, $((\Omega ,\pi ),P_{i})$ is a correlated equilibrium if no player can improve his or her expected utility via a strategy modification.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] In this game two individuals are challenging each other to a contest where each can either *dare* or *chicken out*.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] If one is going to dare, it is better for the other to chicken out.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] But if one is going to chicken out, it is better for the other to dare.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] This leads to an interesting situation where each wants to dare, but only if the other might chicken out.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] In this game, there are three Nash equilibria.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] The two pure strategy Nash equilibria are (*D*, *C*) and (*C*, *D*).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] There is also a mixed strategy equilibrium where both players chicken out with probability 2/3.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] Now consider a third party (or some natural event) that draws one of three cards labeled: (*C*, *C*), (*D*, *C*), and (*C*, *D*), with the same probability, i.e. probability 1/3 for each card.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] After drawing the card the third party informs the players of the strategies assigned to them and to their opponent on the card.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] Suppose a player is assigned *D*, they would not want to deviate supposing the other player played their assigned strategy since they will get 7 (the highest payoff possible).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] Then the other player will play *C* with probability 1/2 and *D* with probability 1/2.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] The expected utility of Daring is 7(1/2) + 0(1/2) = 3.5 and the expected utility of chickening out is 2(1/2) + 6(1/2) = 4.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] So, the player would prefer chickening out.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] Since neither player has an incentive to deviate, this is a correlated equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] The expected payoff for this equilibrium is 7(1/3) + 2(1/3) + 6(1/3) = 5 which is higher than the expected payoff of the mixed strategy Nash equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] The following correlated equilibrium has an even higher payoff to both players: Recommend (*C*, *C*) with probability 1/2, and (*D*, *C*) and (*C*, *D*) with probability 1/4 each.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] Then when a player is recommended to play *C*, they know that the other player will play *D* with (conditional) probability 1/3 and *C* with probability 2/3, and gets expected payoff 14/3, which is equal to (not less than) the expected payoff when they play *D*.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] In this correlated equilibrium, both players get 5.25 in expectation.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] It can be shown that this is the correlated equilibrium with maximal sum of expected payoffs to the two players.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] One of the advantages of correlated equilibria is that they are computationally less expensive than Nash equilibria.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] This can be captured by the fact that computing a correlated equilibrium only requires solving a linear program whereas solving a Nash equilibrium requires finding its fixed point completely.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/correlated-equilibrium] Another way of seeing this is that it is possible for two players to respond to each other's historical plays of a game and end up converging to a correlated equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] The **Lemke–Howson algorithm** is an algorithm that computes a Nash equilibrium of a bimatrix game, named after its inventors, Carlton E.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] It is said to be "the best known among the combinatorial algorithms for finding a Nash equilibrium", although more recently the Porter-Nudelman-Shoham algorithm has outperformed on a number of benchmarks.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] The input to the algorithm is a 2-player game *G*.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] Here, *G* is represented by two *m* × *n* game matrices *A* and *B*, containing the payoffs for players 1 and 2 respectively, who have *m* and *n* pure strategies respectively.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] In the following, one assumes that all payoffs are positive.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] Here, *P*1 represents the set of unnormalized probability distributions over player 1's *m* pure strategies, such that player 2's expected payoff is at most 1.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] The first *m* constraints require the probabilities to be non-negative, and the other *n* constraints require each of the *n* pure strategies of player 2 to have an expected payoff of at most 1.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] *P*2 has a similar meaning, reversing the roles of the players.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] Each vertex *v* of *P*1 is associated with a set of labels from the set {1,...,*m* + *n*} as follows.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] For *j* ∈ {1, ..., *n*}, vertex *v* gets the label *m* + *j* if $B_{1,j}x_{1}+\dots +B_{m,j}x_{m}=1.$ Assuming that *P*1 is nondegenerate, each vertex is incident to *m* facets of *P*1 and has *m* labels.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] Note that the origin, which is a vertex of *P*1, has the labels {1, ..., *m*}.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] Each vertex *w* of *P*2 is associated with a set of labels from the set {1, ..., *m* + *n*} as follows.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] For *i* ∈ {1, ..., *m*}, vertex *w* gets the label *i* if $A_{i,1}x_{m+1}+\dots +A_{i,n}x_{m+n}=1.$ Assuming that *P*2 is nondegenerate, each vertex is incident to *n* facets of *P*2 and has *n* labels.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] Note that the origin, which is a vertex of *P*2, has the labels {*m* + 1, ..., *m* + *n*}.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] The pairs of vertices (*v*,*w*) is said to be *completely labeled* if the sets associated with *v* and *w* contain all labels {1, ..., *m* + *n*}.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] Note that if *v* and *w* are the origins of **R***m* and **R***n* respectively, then (*v*,*w*) is completely labeled.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] The pairs of vertices (*v*,*w*) is said to be *almost completely labeled* (with respect to some missing label *g*) if the sets associated with *v* and *w* contain all labels in {1, ..., *m* + *n*} other than *g*.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] Note that in this case, there will be a *duplicate label* that is associated with both *v* and *w*.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] A *pivot operation* consists of taking some pair (*v*,*w*) and replacing *v* with some vertex adjacent to *v* in *P*1, or alternatively replacing *w* with some vertex adjacent to *w* in *P*2.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] This has the effect (in the case that *v* is replaced) of replacing some label of *v* with some other label.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] The replaced label is said to be *dropped*.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] Given any label of *v*, it is possible to drop that label by moving to a vertex adjacent to *v* that does not contain the hyperplane associated with that label.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] The algorithm starts at the completely labeled pair (*v*,*w*) consisting of the pair of origins.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] An arbitrary label *g* is dropped via a pivot operation, taking us to an almost completely labeled pair (*v′*,*w′*).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] Any almost completely labeled pair admits two pivot operations corresponding to dropping one or other copy of its duplicated label, and each of these operations may result in another almost completely labeled pair, or a completely labeled pair.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] Eventually, the algorithm finds a completely labeled pair (*v**,*w**), which is not the origin.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] (*v**,*w**) corresponds to a pair of unnormalised probability distributions in which every strategy *i* of player 1 either pays that player 1, or pays less than 1 and is played with probability 0 by that player (and a similar observation holds for player 2).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] Normalizing these values to probability distributions, one has a Nash equilibrium (whose payoffs to the players are the inverses of the normalization factors).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] The algorithm can find at most *n* + *m* different Nash equilibria.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] Any choice of initially dropped label determines the equilibrium that is eventually found by the algorithm.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] The Lemke–Howson algorithm is equivalent to the following homotopy-based approach.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] Modify *G* by selecting an arbitrary pure strategy *g*, and giving the player who owns that strategy, a large payment *B* to play it.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] In the modified game, the strategy *g* is played with probability 1, and the other player will play their best response to *g* with probability 1.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] Consider the continuum of games in which *B* is continuously reduced to 0.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] There exists a path of Nash equilibria connecting the unique equilibrium of the modified game, to an equilibrium of *G*.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] The pure strategy *g* chosen to receive the bonus *B* corresponds to the initially dropped label.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] While the algorithm is efficient in practice, in the worst case the number of pivot operations may need to be exponential in the number of pure strategies in the game.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/lemke-howson-algorithm] Subsequently, it has been shown that it is PSPACE-complete to find any of the solutions that can be obtained with the Lemke–Howson algorithm.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In game theory, a **Nash equilibrium** is a situation where no player could gain more by changing their own strategy (holding all other players' strategies fixed) in a game.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] A Nash equilibrium is the most commonly used solution concept for non-cooperative games.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In a game in which Carol and Dan are also players, (A, B, C, D) is a Nash equilibrium if A is Alice's best response to (B, C, D), B is Bob's best response to (A, C, D), and so forth.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The concept of a Nash equilibrium dates back to the time of Cournot, who in 1838 applied it to his model of competition in an oligopoly.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] John Nash showed that there is a Nash equilibrium, possibly in mixed strategies, for every finite game.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Game theorists use Nash equilibrium to analyze the outcome of the strategic interaction of several decision makers.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In a strategic interaction, the outcome for each decision-maker depends on the decisions of the others as well as their own.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The insight underlying Nash's idea is that one cannot predict the choices of multiple decision makers if one analyzes those decisions in isolation.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Instead, one must ask what each player would do taking into account what the player expects the others to do.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] A Nash equilibrium is achieved when no player can improve their outcome by changing their decision, assuming the other players' choices remain unchanged.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The concept has been used to analyze hostile situations such as wars and arms races (see prisoner's dilemma), and also how conflict may be mitigated by repeated interaction (see tit-for-tat).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] It has also been used to study to what extent people with different preferences can cooperate (see battle of the sexes), and whether they will take risks to achieve a cooperative outcome (see stag hunt).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] It has been used to study the adoption of technical standards, and also the occurrence of bank runs and currency crises (see coordination game).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Nash equilibrium is named after American mathematician John Forbes Nash Jr.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The same idea was used in a particular application in 1838 by Antoine Augustin Cournot in his theory of oligopoly.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In Cournot's theory, each of several firms choose how much output to produce to maximize its profit.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The best output for one firm depends on the outputs of the others.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] A Cournot equilibrium occurs when each firm's output maximizes its profits given the output of the other firms, which is a pure-strategy Nash equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Cournot also introduced the concept of best response dynamics in his analysis of the stability of equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Cournot did not use the idea in any other applications, however, or define it generally.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The modern concept of Nash equilibrium is instead defined in terms of mixed strategies, where players choose a probability distribution over possible pure strategies (which might put 100% of the probability on one pure strategy; such pure strategies are a subset of mixed strategies).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The concept of a mixed-strategy equilibrium was introduced by John von Neumann and Oskar Morgenstern in their 1944 book *The Theory of Games and Economic Behavior*, but their analysis was restricted to the special case of zero-sum games.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] They showed that a mixed-strategy Nash equilibrium will exist for any zero-sum game with a finite set of actions.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The contribution of Nash in his 1951 article "Non-Cooperative Games" was to define a mixed-strategy Nash equilibrium for any game with a finite set of actions and prove that at least one (mixed-strategy) Nash equilibrium must exist in such a game.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The key to Nash's ability to prove existence far more generally than von Neumann lay in his definition of equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] According to Nash, "an equilibrium point is an n-tuple such that each player's mixed strategy maximizes [their] payoff if the strategies of the others are held fixed.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Thus each player's strategy is optimal against those of the others." Putting the problem in this framework allowed Nash to employ the Kakutani fixed-point theorem in his 1950 paper to prove existence of equilibria.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] His 1951 paper used the simpler Brouwer fixed-point theorem for the same purpose.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Game theorists have discovered that in some circumstances Nash equilibrium makes invalid predictions or fails to make a unique prediction.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] They have proposed many solution concepts ('refinements' of Nash equilibria) designed to rule out implausible Nash equilibria.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] One particularly important issue is that some Nash equilibria may be based on threats that are not 'credible'.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In 1965 Reinhard Selten proposed subgame perfect equilibrium as a refinement that eliminates equilibria which depend on non-credible threats.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Other extensions of the Nash equilibrium concept have addressed what happens if a game is repeated, or what happens if a game is played in the absence of complete information.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] However, subsequent refinements and extensions of Nash equilibrium share the main insight on which Nash's concept rests: the equilibrium is a set of strategies such that each player's strategy is optimal given the choices of the others.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] A strategy profile is a set of strategies, one for each player.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Informally, a strategy profile is a Nash equilibrium if no player can do better by unilaterally changing their strategy.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] To see what this means, imagine that each player is told the strategies of the others.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] For instance if a player prefers "Yes", then that set of strategies is not a Nash equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] But if every player prefers not to switch (or is indifferent between switching and not) then the strategy profile is a Nash equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Thus, each strategy in a Nash equilibrium is a best response to the other players' strategies in that equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Formally, let $S_{i}$ be the set of all possible strategies for player i , where $i=1,\ldots ,N$ .
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Let $s^{*}=(s_{i}^{*},s_{-i}^{*})$ be a strategy profile, a set consisting of one strategy for each player, where $s_{-i}^{*}$ denotes the $N-1$ strategies of all the players except i .
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Let $u_{i}(s_{i},s_{-i}^{*})$ be player *i*'s payoff as a function of the strategies.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] A game can have more than one Nash equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Even if the equilibrium is unique, it might be *weak*: a player might be indifferent among several strategies given the other players' choices.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The strategy set $S_{i}$ can be different for different players, and its elements can be a variety of mathematical objects.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Nash's existence proofs assume a finite strategy set, but the concept of Nash equilibrium does not require it.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] A game can have a pure-strategy or a mixed-strategy Nash equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In the latter, not every player always plays the same strategy.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Instead, there is a probability distribution over different strategies.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] If every player's answer is "Yes", then the equilibrium is classified as a *strict Nash equilibrium*.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] If instead, for some player, there is exact equality between the strategy in Nash equilibrium and some other strategy that gives exactly the same payout (i.e., the player is indifferent between switching and not), then the equilibrium is classified as a *weak* or *non-strict Nash equilibrium*.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The Nash equilibrium defines stability only in terms of individual player deviations.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In cooperative games such a concept is not convincing enough.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Strong Nash equilibrium allows for deviations by every conceivable coalition.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Formally, a strong Nash equilibrium is a Nash equilibrium in which no coalition, taking the actions of its complements as given, can cooperatively deviate in a way that benefits all of its members.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] However, the strong Nash concept is sometimes perceived as too "strong" in that the environment allows for unlimited private communication.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In fact, strong Nash equilibrium has to be weakly Pareto efficient.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] As a result of these requirements, strong Nash is too rare to be useful in many branches of game theory.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] However, in games such as elections with many more players than possible outcomes, it can be more common than a stable equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] A refined Nash equilibrium known as coalition-proof Nash equilibrium (CPNE) occurs when players cannot do better even if they are allowed to communicate and make "self-enforcing" agreement to deviate.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Every correlated strategy supported by iterated strict dominance and on the Pareto frontier is a CPNE.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Further, it is possible for a game to have a Nash equilibrium that is resilient against coalitions less than a specified size, k.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] CPNE is related to the theory of the core.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Nash equilibria need not exist if the set of choices is infinite and non-compact.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] However, a Nash equilibrium exists if the set of choices is compact with each player's payoff continuous in the strategies of all the players.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Nash's existence theorem has been extended to more general classes of games.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In Nash's model, the set of strategies available to each player is fixed and does not depend on the other players' strategies.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] A more general model allows these sets to depend on other players' strategies; this is often called **coupled constraints**.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In Nash's model, the set of possible strategy-profiles is a Cartesian product of the players' strategy sets, whereas in the more general model it can be an arbitrary set.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] When there are coupled constraints, the equilibrium is often called **Generalized Nash equilibrium** **(GNE)**.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Rosen proved that, if the set of strategy-profiles is any convex set, and the utility function of each player is continuous in all strategies and a concave function of the player's own strategy, then a GNE exists; see **concave games**.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Nash considered games with finitely many players, in **non-atomic games** the set of players is infinite - there is a continuum of players David Schmeidler proved that an equilibrium exists under certain conditions.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The Nash equilibrium may sometimes appear non-rational in a third-person perspective.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] This is because a Nash equilibrium is not necessarily Pareto optimal.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Nash equilibrium may also have non-rational consequences in sequential games because players may "threaten" each other with threats they would not actually carry out.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] For such games the subgame perfect Nash equilibrium may be more meaningful as a tool of analysis.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The *coordination game* is a classic two-player, two-strategy game, as shown in the example payoff matrix to the right.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] There are two pure-strategy equilibria, (A,A) with payoff 4 for each player and (B,B) with payoff 2 for each.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The combination (B,B) is a Nash equilibrium because if either player unilaterally changes their strategy from B to A, their payoff will fall from 2 to 1.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] A famous example of a coordination game is the stag hunt.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Two players may choose to hunt a stag or a rabbit, the stag providing more meat (4 utility units, 2 for each player) than the rabbit (1 utility unit).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The caveat is that the stag must be cooperatively hunted, so if one player attempts to hunt the stag, while the other hunts the rabbit, the stag hunter will totally fail, for a payoff of 0, whereas the rabbit hunter will succeed, for a payoff of 1.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The game has two equilibria, (stag, stag) and (rabbit, rabbit), because a player's optimal strategy depends on their expectation on what the other player will do.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] If one hunter trusts that the other will hunt the stag, they should hunt the stag; however if they think the other will hunt the rabbit, they too will hunt the rabbit.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] This game is used as an analogy for social cooperation, since much of the benefit that people gain in society depends upon people cooperating and implicitly trusting one another to act in a manner corresponding with cooperation.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Driving on a road against an oncoming car, and having to choose either to swerve on the left or to swerve on the right of the road, is also a coordination game.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In this case there are two pure-strategy Nash equilibria, when both choose to either drive on the left or on the right.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] We add another where the probabilities for each player are (50%, 50%).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] An application of Nash equilibria is in determining the expected flow of traffic in a network.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] If we assume that there are x "cars" traveling from A to D, what is the expected distribution of traffic in the network?
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] This situation can be modeled as a "game", where every traveler has a choice of 3 strategies and where each strategy is a route from A to D (one of ABD, ABCD, or ACD).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The "payoff" of each strategy is the travel time of each route.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In the graph on the right, a car travelling via ABD experiences travel time of $1+{\frac {x}{100}}+2$ , where x is the number of cars traveling on edge AB.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Thus, payoffs for any given strategy depend on the choices of the other players, as is usual.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] However, the goal, in this case, is to minimize travel time, not maximize it.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Equilibrium will occur when the time on all paths is exactly the same.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] When that happens, no single driver has any incentive to switch routes, since it can only add to their travel time.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] For the graph on the right, if, for example, 100 cars are travelling from A to D, then equilibrium will occur when 25 drivers travel via ABD, 50 via ABCD, and 25 via ACD.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Every driver now has a total travel time of 3.75 (to see this, a total of 75 cars take the AB edge, and likewise, 75 cars take the CD edge).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Notice that this distribution is not, actually, socially optimal.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] If the 100 cars agreed that 50 travel via ABD and the other 50 through ACD, then travel time for any single car would actually be 3.5, which is less than 3.75.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] This is also the Nash equilibrium if the path between B and C is removed, which means that adding another possible route can decrease the efficiency of the system, a phenomenon known as Braess's paradox.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] This can be illustrated by a two-player game in which both players simultaneously choose an integer from 0 to 3 and they both win the smaller of the two numbers in points.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In addition, if one player chooses a larger number than the other, then they have to give up two points to the other.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] This game has a unique pure-strategy Nash equilibrium: both players choosing 0 (highlighted in light red).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Any other strategy can be improved by a player switching their number to one less than that of the other player.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In the adjacent table, if the game begins at the green square, it is in player 1's interest to move to the purple square and it is in player 2's interest to move to the blue square.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Although it would not fit the definition of a competition game, if the game is modified so that the two players win the named amount if they both choose the same number, and otherwise win nothing, then there are 4 Nash equilibria: (0,0), (1,1), (2,2), and (3,3).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] There is an easy numerical way to identify Nash equilibria on a payoff matrix.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] It is especially helpful in two-person games where players have more than two strategies.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In this case formal analysis may become too long.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] This rule does not apply to the case where mixed (stochastic) strategies are of interest.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The rule goes as follows: if the first payoff number, in the payoff pair of the cell, is the maximum of the column of the cell and if the second number is the maximum of the row of the cell – then the cell represents a Nash equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Using the rule, we can very quickly (much faster than with formal analysis) see that the Nash equilibria cells are (B,A), (A,B), and (C,C).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Indeed, for cell (B,A), 40 is the maximum of the first column and 25 is the maximum of the second row.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] For (A,B), 25 is the maximum of the second column and 40 is the maximum of the first row; the same applies for cell (C,C).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] For other cells, either one or both of the duplet members are not the maximum of the corresponding rows and columns.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] This said, the actual mechanics of finding equilibrium cells is obvious: find the maximum of a column and check if the second member of the pair is the maximum of the row.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] If these conditions are met, the cell represents a Nash equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Check all columns this way to find all NE cells.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] An N×N matrix may have between 0 and N×N pure-strategy Nash equilibria.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The concept of stability, useful in the analysis of many kinds of equilibria, can also be applied to Nash equilibria.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] 2. the player who did change is now playing with a strictly worse strategy.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] If these cases are both met, then a player with the small change in their mixed strategy will return immediately to the Nash equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] If condition one does not hold then the equilibrium is unstable.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] If only condition one holds then there are likely to be an infinite number of optimal strategies for the player who changed.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In the "driving game" example above there are both stable and unstable equilibria.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The equilibria involving mixed strategies with 100% probabilities are stable.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] If either player changes their probabilities slightly, they will be both at a disadvantage, and their opponent will have no reason to change their strategy in turn.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] If either player changes their probabilities (which would neither benefit or damage the expectation of the player who did the change, if the other player's mixed strategy is still (50%,50%)), then the other player immediately has a better strategy at either (0%, 100%) or (100%, 0%).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Stability is crucial in practical applications of Nash equilibria, since the mixed strategy of each player is not perfectly known, but has to be inferred from statistical distribution of their actions in the game.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In this case unstable equilibria are very unlikely to arise in practice, since any minute change in the proportions of each strategy seen will lead to a change in strategy and the breakdown of the equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Finally in the eighties, building with great depth on such ideas Mertens-stable equilibria were introduced as a solution concept.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Mertens stable equilibria satisfy both forward induction and backward induction.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In a game theory context stable equilibria now usually refer to Mertens stable equilibria.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] If a game has a unique Nash equilibrium and is played among players under certain conditions, then the NE strategy set will be adopted.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The players have sufficient intelligence to deduce the solution.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The players know the planned equilibrium strategy of all of the other players.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The players believe that a deviation in their own strategy will not cause deviations by any other players.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] There is common knowledge that all players meet these conditions, including this one.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] So, not only must each player know the other players meet the conditions, but also they must know that they all know that they meet them, and know that they know that they know that they meet them, and so on.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Intentional or accidental imperfection in execution.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] For example, a computer capable of flawless logical play facing a second flawless computer will result in equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Introduction of imperfection will lead to its disruption either through loss to the player who makes the mistake, or through negation of the common knowledge criterion leading to possible victory for the player.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] (An example would be a player suddenly putting the car into reverse in the game of chicken, ensuring a no-loss no-win scenario).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In many cases, the third condition is not met because, even though the equilibrium must exist, it is unknown due to the complexity of the game, for instance in Chinese chess.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Or, if known, it may not be known to all players, as when playing tic-tac-toe with a small child who desperately wants to win (meeting the other criteria).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The criterion of common knowledge may not be met even if all players do, in fact, meet all the other criteria.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Players wrongly distrusting each other's rationality may adopt counter-strategies to expected irrational play on their opponents’ behalf.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] This is a major consideration in "chicken" or an arms race, for example.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In his Ph.D. dissertation, John Nash proposed two interpretations of his equilibrium concept, with the objective of showing how equilibrium points can be connected with observable phenomena.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In this case, the conjectures need only be mutually known).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] For a formal result along these lines, see Kuhn, H. and et al., 1996, "The Work of John Nash in Game Theory", *Journal of Economic Theory*, 69, 153–185.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Due to the limited conditions in which NE can actually be observed, they are rarely treated as a guide to day-to-day behaviour, or observed in practice in human negotiations.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] However, as a theoretical concept in economics and evolutionary biology, the NE has explanatory power.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The payoff in economics is utility (or sometimes money), and in evolutionary biology is gene transmission; both are the fundamental bottom line of survival.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Researchers who apply games theory in these fields claim that strategies failing to maximize these for whatever reason will be competed out of the market or environment, which are ascribed the ability to test all strategies.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] This conclusion is drawn from the "stability" theory above.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In these situations the assumption that the strategy observed is actually a NE has often been borne out by research.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The Nash equilibrium is a superset of the subgame perfect Nash equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The subgame perfect equilibrium in addition to the Nash equilibrium requires that the strategy also is a Nash equilibrium in every subgame of that game.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] This eliminates all non-credible threats, that is, strategies that contain non-rational moves in order to make the counter-player change their strategy.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The image to the right shows a simple sequential game that illustrates the issue with subgame imperfect Nash equilibria.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In this game player one chooses left(L) or right(R), which is followed by player two being called upon to be kind (K) or unkind (U) to player one, However, player two only stands to gain from being unkind if player one goes left.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] If player one goes right the rational player two would de facto be kind to her/him in that subgame.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] However, The non-credible threat of being unkind at 2(2) is still part of the blue (L, (U,U)) Nash equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Therefore, if rational behavior can be expected by both parties the subgame perfect Nash equilibrium may be a more meaningful solution concept when such dynamic inconsistencies arise.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Nash's original proof (in his thesis) used Brouwer's fixed-point theorem (e.g., see below for a variant).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] This section presents a simpler proof via the Kakutani fixed-point theorem, following Nash's 1950 paper (he credits David Gale with the observation that such a simplification is possible).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Here, $\sigma \in \Sigma$ , where $\Sigma =\Sigma _{i}\times \Sigma _{-i}$ , is a mixed-strategy profile in the set of all mixed strategies and $u_{i}$ is the payoff function for player i.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Define a set-valued function $r\colon \Sigma \rightarrow 2^{\Sigma }$ such that $r=r_{i}(\sigma _{-i})\times r_{-i}(\sigma _{i})$ .
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The existence of a Nash equilibrium is equivalent to r having a fixed point.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Kakutani's fixed point theorem guarantees the existence of a fixed point if the following four conditions are satisfied.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Condition 1. is satisfied from the fact that $\Sigma$ is a simplex and thus compact.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Convexity follows from players' ability to mix strategies. $\Sigma$ is nonempty as long as players have strategies.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Condition 2. and 3. are satisfied by way of Berge's maximum theorem.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Because $u_{i}$ is continuous and compact, $r(\sigma _{i})$ is non-empty and upper hemicontinuous.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Condition 4. is satisfied as a result of mixed strategies.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Suppose $\sigma _{i},\sigma '_{i}\in r(\sigma _{-i})$ , then $\lambda \sigma _{i}+(1-\lambda )\sigma '_{i}\in r(\sigma _{-i})$ . i.e. if two strategies maximize payoffs, then a mix between the two strategies will yield the same payoff.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Therefore, there exists a fixed point in r and a Nash equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] When Nash made this point to John von Neumann in 1949, von Neumann famously dismissed it with the words, "That's trivial, you know.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] That's just a fixed-point theorem." (See Nasar, 1998, p.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] We have a game $G=(N,A,u)$ where N is the number of players and $A=A_{1}\times \cdots \times A_{N}$ is the action set for the players.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] All of the action sets $A_{i}$ are finite.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Let $\Delta =\Delta _{1}\times \cdots \times \Delta _{N}$ denote the set of mixed strategies for the players.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The finiteness of the $A_{i}$ s ensures the compactness of $\Delta$ .
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The gain function represents the benefit a player gets by unilaterally changing their strategy.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] It is easy to see that each $f_{i}$ is a valid mixed strategy in $\Delta _{i}$ .
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] It is also easy to check that each $f_{i}$ is a continuous function of $\sigma$ , and hence f is a continuous function.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] As the cross product of a finite number of compact convex sets, $\Delta$ is also compact and convex.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Applying the Brouwer fixed point theorem to f and $\Delta$ we conclude that f has a fixed point in $\Delta$ , call it $\sigma ^{*}$ .
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] We claim that $\sigma ^{*}$ is a Nash equilibrium in G .
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] This simply states that each player gains no benefit by unilaterally changing their strategy, which is exactly the necessary condition for a Nash equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Now assume that the gains are not all zero.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Also we shall denote ${\text{Gain}}(i,\cdot )$ as the gain vector indexed by actions in $A_{i}$ .
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Since $C>1$ we have that $\sigma _{i}^{*}$ is some positive scaling of the vector ${\text{Gain}}_{i}(\sigma ^{*},\cdot )$ .
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] To see this, first if ${\text{Gain}}_{i}(\sigma ^{*},a)>0$ then this is true by definition of the gain function.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] and so the left term is zero, giving us that the entire expression is 0 as needed.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] where the last inequality follows since $\sigma _{i}^{*}$ is a non-zero vector.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] But this is a clear contradiction, so all the gains must indeed be zero.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Therefore, $\sigma ^{*}$ is a Nash equilibrium for G as needed.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] If a player A has a dominant strategy $s_{A}$ then there exists a Nash equilibrium in which A plays $s_{A}$ .
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In the case of two players A and B, there exists a Nash equilibrium in which A plays $s_{A}$ and B plays a best response to $s_{A}$ .
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] If $s_{A}$ is a strictly dominant strategy, A plays $s_{A}$ in all Nash equilibria.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] If both A and B have strictly dominant strategies, there exists a unique Nash equilibrium in which each plays their strictly dominant strategy.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In games with mixed-strategy Nash equilibria, the probability of a player choosing any particular (so pure) strategy can be computed by assigning a variable to each strategy that represents a fixed probability for choosing that strategy.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In order for a player to be willing to randomize, their expected payoff for each (pure) strategy should be the same.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In addition, the sum of the probabilities for each strategy of a particular player should be 1.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] This creates a system of equations from which the probabilities of choosing each strategy can be derived.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In the matching pennies game, player A loses a point to B if A and B play the same strategy and wins a point from B if they play different strategies.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] To compute the mixed-strategy Nash equilibrium, assign A the probability p of playing H and $(1-p)$ of playing T, and assign B the probability q of playing H and $(1-q)$ of playing T.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Thus, a mixed-strategy Nash equilibrium in this game is for each player to randomly choose H or T with $p={\frac {1}{2}}$ and $q={\frac {1}{2}}$ .
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In 1971, Robert Wilson came up with the "oddness theorem", which says that "almost all" finite games have a finite and odd number of Nash equilibria.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In 1973, Harsanyi published an alternative proof of the result.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] "Almost all" here means that any game with an infinite or even number of equilibria is very special in the sense that if its payoffs were even slightly randomly perturbed, with probability one it would have an odd number of equilibria instead.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The prisoner's dilemma, for example, has one equilibrium, while the battle of the sexes has three—two pure and one mixed, and this remains true even if the payoffs change slightly.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] The free money game is an example of a "special" game with an even number of equilibria.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In it, two players have to both vote "yes" rather than "no" to get a reward and the votes are simultaneous.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] There are two pure-strategy Nash equilibria, (yes, yes) and (no, no), and no mixed strategy equilibria, because the strategy "yes" weakly dominates "no".
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] "Yes" is as good as "no" regardless of the other player's action, but if there is any chance the other player chooses "yes" then "yes" is the best reply.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Under a small random perturbation of the payoffs, however, the probability that any two payoffs would remain tied, whether at 0 or some other number, is vanishingly small, and the game would have either one or three equilibria instead.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In 1950 Nash proved that every n -person normal form game has a Nash equilibrium (NE) in mixed strategies.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Yet, there are large families of games that have NE in pure strategies, for example, finite n -person positional (graphical) games with perfect information.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] In case of two players, Nash solvability in pure strategies is equivalent to duality of hypergraphs.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Later this result was extended for the non-zero sum case.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Interestingly, in such NE the strategy of one player doesn't depend on the preferences of the other.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] But the opposite is not necessarily true.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] One can check all 4 pure-strategy profiles (the 4 cells in the matrix), and verify that in all of them, one of the players has a profitable deviation, so there is no Nash equilibrium.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] On the other hand, the minimax value of the row player is 1 (R-T) and the minimax value of the column player is 1 (B-R).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] Hence, the strategy profile R-T is minmax-acceptable.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] There are games in which even a minmax-acceptable strategy profile does not exist.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/nash-equilibrium] For example, in Matching pennies, the minimax values (with pure strategies) are 1,1, but the sum of payments is 0, so no strategy profile can give 1 to both players.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] In computer science, **PPAD** ("Polynomial Parity Arguments on Directed graphs") is a complexity class introduced by Christos Papadimitriou in 1994.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] PPAD is a subclass of TFNP based on functions that can be shown to be total by a parity argument.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] PPAD is a subset of the class TFNP, the class of function problems in FNP that are guaranteed to be total.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] Subclasses of TFNP are defined based on the type of mathematical proof used to prove that a solution always exists.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] Informally, PPAD is the subclass of TFNP where the guarantee that there exists a *y* such that P(*x*,*y*) holds is based on a parity argument on a directed graph.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] having at most one predecessor and at most one successor.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] Such a *t* must exist if an *s* does, because the structure of G means that vertices with only one neighbour come in pairs.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] In particular, given *s*, we can find such a *t* at the other end of the string starting at *s*.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] In many cases, when a problem is said to "be in PPAD", it often means that finding an *approximate* solution to the problem is in PPAD.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] This is often necessary, as in many cases, the solutions might involve irrational numbers, and thus cannot be output in finite time.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] However, there are cases in which solutions with rational numbers are guaranteed to exist.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] For such cases, Filos-Ratsikas, Hansen, Høgh and Hollender present a general method for proving that computing an *exact* solution belongs to PPAD.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] PPAD is contained in (but not known to be equal to) PPA (the corresponding class of parity arguments for *undirected* graphs) which is contained in TFNP.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] PPAD is also contained in (but not known to be equal to) PPP, another subclass of TFNP.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] PPAD is a class of problems that are believed to be hard, but obtaining PPAD-completeness is a weaker evidence of intractability than that of obtaining NP-completeness.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] PPAD problems cannot be NP-complete, for the technical reason that NP is a class of decision problems, but the answer of PPAD problems is always yes, as a solution is known to exist, even though it might be hard to find that solution.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] However, PPAD and NP are closely related.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] While the question whether a Nash equilibrium exists for a given game cannot be NP-hard because the answer is always yes, the question whether a *second* equilibrium exists is NP complete.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] Examples of PPAD-complete problems include finding Nash equilibria, computing fixed points in Brouwer functions, and finding Arrow-Debreu equilibria in markets.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] Fearnley, Goldberg, Hollender and Savani proved that a complexity class called CLS is equal to the intersection of PPAD and PLS.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] Etessami and Yannakakis (who invented the related class FIXP) write that "The piecewise-linear fragment of FIXP equals PPAD".
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/ppad-complexity] In other words, the problems in PPAD are the problems in FIXP in which the input function is piecewise-linear.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] In mathematics, **Sperner's lemma** is a combinatorial result on colorings of triangulations, analogous to the Brouwer fixed point theorem, which is equivalent to it.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] It states that every **Sperner coloring** (described below) of a triangulation of an n -dimensional simplex contains a cell whose vertices all have different colors.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] The initial result of this kind was proved by Emanuel Sperner, in relation with proofs of invariance of domain.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Sperner colorings have been used for effective computation of fixed points and in root-finding algorithms, and are applied in fair division (cake cutting) algorithms.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] According to the Soviet *Mathematical Encyclopaedia* (ed.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Vinogradov), a related 1929 theorem (of Knaster, Borsuk and Mazurkiewicz) had also become known as the *Sperner lemma* – this point is discussed in the English translation (ed.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] It is now commonly known as the Knaster–Kuratowski–Mazurkiewicz lemma.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] In one dimension, Sperner's Lemma can be regarded as a discrete version of the intermediate value theorem.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] In this case, it essentially says that if a discrete function takes only the values 0 and 1, begins at the value 0 and ends at the value 1, then it must switch values an odd number of times.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] The two-dimensional case is the one referred to most frequently.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Subdivide a triangle ABC arbitrarily into a triangulation consisting of smaller triangles meeting edge to edge.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] The vertices that lie along any edge of triangle ABC have only two colors, the two colors at the endpoints of the edge.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] For example, each vertex on AC must have the same color as A or C.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Then every Sperner coloring of every triangulation has at least one "rainbow triangle", a smaller triangle in the triangulation that has its vertices colored with all three different colors.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] More precisely, there must be an odd number of rainbow triangles.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Consider any triangulation T, a disjoint division of ${\mathcal {A}}$ into smaller n-dimensional simplices, again meeting face-to-face.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Then every Sperner coloring of every triangulation of the n-dimensional simplex has an odd number of instances of a *rainbow simplex*, meaning a simplex whose vertices are colored with all *n* + 1 colors.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] In particular, there must be at least one rainbow simplex.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] We shall first address the two-dimensional case.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Two vertices are connected with an edge if their corresponding areas share a common border with one endpoint colored 1 and the other colored 2.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Note that on the interval AB there is an odd number of borders colored 1-2 (simply because A is colored 1, B is colored 2; and as we move along AB, there must be an odd number of color changes in order to get different colors at the beginning and at the end).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] On the intervals BC and CA, there are no borders colored 1-2 at all.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Therefore, the vertex of G corresponding to the outer area has an odd degree.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] By the handshaking lemma, G has an even number of vertices with odd degree.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Therefore, the remaining graph, excluding the outer area, has an odd number of vertices with odd degree corresponding to members of T.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] It can be easily seen that the only possible degree of a triangle from T is 0, 1, or 2, and that the degree 1 corresponds to a triangle colored with the three colors 1, 2, and 3.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Thus we have obtained a slightly stronger conclusion, which says that in a triangulation T there is an odd number (and at least one) of full-colored triangles.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] A multidimensional case can be proved by induction on the dimension of a simplex.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] We apply the same reasoning, as in the two-dimensional case, to conclude that in a n-dimensional triangulation there is an odd number of full-colored simplices.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Here is an elaboration of the proof given previously, for a reader new to graph theory.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] This diagram numbers the colors of the vertices of the example given previously.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] The small triangles whose vertices all have different numbers are shaded in the graph.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Each small triangle becomes a node in the new graph derived from the triangulation.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] The small letters identify the areas, eight inside the figure, and area i designates the space outside of it.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] As described previously, those nodes that share an edge whose endpoints are numbered 1 and 2 are joined in the derived graph.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] For example, node d shares an edge with the outer area i, and its vertices all have different numbers, so it is also shaded.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Node b is not shaded because two vertices have the same number, but it is joined to the outer area.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] One could add a new full-numbered triangle, say by inserting a node numbered 3 into the edge between 1 and 1 of node a, and joining that node to the other vertex of a.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Doing so would have to create a pair of new nodes, like the situation with nodes f and g.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Andrew McLennan and Rabee Tourky presented a different proof, using the volume of a simplex.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] It proceeds in one step, with no induction.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Suppose there is a *d*-dimensional simplex of side-length *N*, and it is triangulated into sub-simplices of side-length 1.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] There is a function that, given any vertex of the triangulation, returns its color.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] The coloring is guaranteed to satisfy Sperner's boundary condition.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] How many times do we have to call the function in order to find a rainbow simplex?
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Obviously, we can go over all the triangulation vertices, whose number is O(*Nd*), which is polynomial in *N* when the dimension is fixed.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] But, can it be done in time O(poly(log *N*)), which is polynomial in the binary representation of N?
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] This problem was first studied by Christos Papadimitriou.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] He introduced a complexity class called PPAD, which contains this as well as related problems (such as finding a Brouwer fixed point).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] He proved that finding a Sperner simplex is PPAD-complete even for *d*=3.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Some 15 years later, Chen and Deng proved PPAD-completeness even for *d*=2.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] It is believed that PPAD-hard problems cannot be solved in time O(poly(log *N*)).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Suppose that each vertex of the triangulation may be labeled with multiple colors, so that the coloring function is *F* : *S* → 2[*n*+1].
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] For every sub-simplex, the set of labelings on its vertices is a set-family over the set of colors [*n* + 1].
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] This set-family can be seen as a hypergraph.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] If, for every vertex v on a face of the simplex, the colors in *f*(*v*) are a subset of the set of colors on the face endpoints, then there exists a sub-simplex with a *balanced labeling* – a labeling in which the corresponding hypergraph admits a perfect fractional matching.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] It is a combinatorial analogue of the KKMS lemma.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Suppose that we have a d-dimensional polytope P with n vertices.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] P is triangulated, and each vertex of the triangulation is labeled with a label from {1, …, *n*}.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] A sub-simplex is called *fully-labeled* if it is d-dimensional, and each of its *d* + 1 vertices has a different label.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] If every vertex in a face F of P is labeled with one of the labels on the endpoints of F, then there are at least *n* – *d* fully-labeled simplices.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] The general statement was conjectured by Atanassov in 1996, who proved it for the case *d* = 2.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] The proof of the general case was first given by de Loera, Peterson, and Su in 2002.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] They provide two proofs: the first is non-constructive and uses the notion of *pebble sets*; the second is constructive and is based on arguments of following paths in graphs.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Meunier extended the theorem from polytopes to *polytopal bodies,* which need not be convex or simply-connected.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] In particular, if P is a polytope, then the set of its faces is a polytopal body.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] fully-labeled simplices such that any pair of these simplices receives two different labelings.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] The degree deg*B*(*P*)(*vi*) is the number of edges of *B*(*P*) to which vi belongs.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Since the degree is at least d, the lower bound is at least *n* – *d*.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Musin further extended the theorem to d-dimensional piecewise-linear manifolds, with or without a boundary.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Asada, Frick, Pisharody, Polevy, Stoner, Tsang and Wellner further extended the theorem to pseudomanifolds with boundary, and improved the lower bound on the number of facets with pairwise-distinct labels.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Suppose that, instead of a simplex triangulated into sub-simplices, we have an n-dimensional cube partitioned into smaller n-dimensional cubes.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Suppose the cube [0,*M*]*n*, for some integer M, is partitioned into Mn unit cubes.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Suppose each vertex of the partition is labeled with a label from {1, …, *n* + 1}, such that for every vertex v: (1) if *vi* = 0 then the label on v is at most i; (2) if *vi*=*M* then the label on v is not i.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Then there exists a unit cube with all the labels {1, …, *n* + 1} (some of them more than once).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] The special case *n* = 2 is: suppose a square is partitioned into sub-squares, and each vertex is labeled with a label from {1,2,3}.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] The left edge is labeled with 1 (= at most 1); the bottom edge is labeled with 1 or 2 (= at most 2); the top edge is labeled with 1 or 3 (= not 2); and the right edge is labeled with 2 or 3 (= not 1).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Then there is a square labeled with 1,2,3.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Another variant, related to the Poincaré–Miranda theorem, is as follows.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Suppose the cube [0,*M*]*n* is partitioned into Mn unit cubes.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Suppose each vertex is labeled with a binary vector of length n, such that for every vertex v: (1) if *vi* = 0 then the coordinate i of label on v is 0; (2) if *vi* = *M* then coordinate i of the label on v is 1; (3) if two vertices are neighbors, then their labels differ by at most one coordinate.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Then there exists a unit cube in which all 2*n* labels are different.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] In two dimensions, another way to formulate this theorem is: in any labeling that satisfies conditions (1) and (2), there is at least one cell in which the sum of labels is 0 [a 1-dimensional cell with (1,1) and (-1,-1) labels, or a 2-dimensional cells with all four different labels].
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Wolsey strengthened these two results by proving that the number of completely-labeled cubes is odd.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Musin extended these results to general quadrangulations.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Suppose that, instead of a single labeling, we have n different Sperner labelings.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] We consider pairs (simplex, permutation) such that, the label of each vertex of the simplex is chosen from a different labeling (so for each simplex, there are *n*! different pairs).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Then there are at least *n*! fully labeled pairs.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] This was proved by Ravindra Bapat for any triangulation.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] A simpler proof, which only works for specific triangulations, was presented later by Su.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Another way to state this lemma is as follows.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Suppose there are n people, each of whom produces a different Sperner labeling of the same triangulation.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Then, there exists a simplex, and a matching of the people to its vertices, such that each vertex is labeled by its owner differently (one person labels its vertex by 1, another person labels its vertex by 2, etc.).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Moreover, there are at least *n*! such matchings.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] This can be used to find an envy-free cake-cutting with connected pieces.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Asada, Frick, Pisharody, Polevy, Stoner, Tsang and Wellner extended this theorem to pseudomanifolds with boundary.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] More generally, suppose we have m different Sperner labelings, where m may be different than n.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] For any positive integers *I*1, …, *Im*whose sum is *m* + *n* – 1, there exists a baby-simplex on which, for every *j* ∈ {1, …, *n*},, the label j is used by at least lj (out of m) different labelings.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Both versions reduce to Sperner's lemma when *m* = 1, or when all m labelings are identical.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Brown and Cairns strengthened Sperner's lemma by considering the *orientation* of simplices.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Each sub-simplex has an orientation that can be either +1 or -1 (if it is fully-labeled), or 0 (if it is not fully-labeled).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] They proved that the sum of all orientations of simplices is +1.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] In particular, this implies that there is an odd number of fully-labeled simplices.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] As an example for *n* = 3, suppose a triangle is triangulated and labeled with {1,2,3}.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Consider the cyclic sequence of labels on the boundary of the triangle.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Define the *degree* of the labeling as the number of switches from 1 to 2, minus the number of switches from 2 to 1.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Note that the degree is the same if we count switches from 2 to 3 minus 3 to 2, or from 3 to 1 minus 1 to 3.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Musin proved that *the number of fully labeled triangles is at least the degree of the labeling*.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] In particular, if the degree is nonzero, then there exists at least one fully labeled triangle.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] If a labeling satisfies the Sperner condition, then its degree is exactly 1: there are 1-2 and 2-1 switches only in the side between vertices 1 and 2, and the number of 1-2 switches must be one more than the number of 2-1 switches (when walking from vertex 1 to vertex 2).
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Therefore, the original Sperner lemma follows from Musin's theorem.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] There is a similar lemma about finite and infinite trees and cycles.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Mirzakhani and Vondrak study a weaker variant of a Sperner labeling, in which the only requirement is that label *i* is not used on the face opposite to vertex *i*.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] They call it *Sperner-admissible labeling*.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] They show that there are Sperner-admissible labelings in which every cell contains at most 4 labels.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] They also prove an optimal lower bound on the number of cells that must have at least two different labels in each Sperner-admissible labeling.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] They also prove that, for any Sperner-admissible partition of the regular simplex, the total area of the boundary between the parts is minimized by the Voronoi partition.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Sperner colorings have been used for effective computation of fixed points.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] A Sperner coloring can be constructed such that fully labeled simplices correspond to fixed points of a given function.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] By making a triangulation smaller and smaller, one can show that the limit of the fully labeled simplices is exactly the fixed point.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Hence, the technique provides a way to approximate fixed points.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] A related application is the numerical detection of periodic orbits and symbolic dynamics.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Sperner's lemma can also be used in root-finding algorithms and fair division algorithms; see Simmons–Su protocols.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Sperner's lemma is one of the key ingredients of the proof of Monsky's theorem, that a square cannot be cut into an odd number of equal-area triangles.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Sperner's lemma can be used to find a competitive equilibrium in an exchange economy, although there are more efficient ways to find it.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Fifty years after first publishing it, Sperner presented a survey on the development, influence and applications of his combinatorial lemma.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] There are several fixed-point theorems which come in three equivalent variants: an algebraic topology variant, a combinatorial variant and a set-covering variant.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Each variant can be proved separately using totally different arguments, but each variant can also be reduced to the other variants in its row.
[src:nash-equilibrium-computation/sperner-s-lemma] Additionally, each result in the top row can be deduced from the one below it in the same column.
